The Trojan Horse of Europe.
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
An emergency grant will have to be allocated.
It will be necessary to impose conditions.
The Greek government will make empty promises.
This should allow the Greek government to pay off its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems to come.
Some will say that the fatal error was to have allowed Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was, however, already obvious that the country was not ready.
Her budget policy was already unfettered when she joined the monetary union in 2001, and her unions were already pressing for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this answer is too simplistic, inasmuch as such signs of malfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and a staggering budget deficit, sees Greece as a reflection of its own future.
And if that's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy do a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face strong budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot proceed with a devaluation of their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to call for help.
All this raises one question: was the true mistake not having created the euro ?
To the extent that I was one of the few Americans encouraging the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking me if I am rethinking my original position.
My answer is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway to the path of a viable monetary union.
If she does nothing, the next crisis might very well make this one seem like a walk in the park.
If she wants to complete her monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, the members of the Union can only afford to lend assistance to Greece by exceeding the regulation that prevents them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or in circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide their aid, public opinion and the markets tend to question their integrity.
If the problems result from the Treaty of Lisbon, then it must be amended.
In addition, aid should not be given solely on certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary control of the national budget by a committee of 'experts' appointed by the European Union.
History shows us that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, countries subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But no one forces them to accept that money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the late Pact on Stability and Growth.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed its budget over to a specially appointed expert, named by the administration of President Barack Obama ?
In fact, it wouldn't bother them that much.
The expert would not be Californian by origin, but American.
Public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the state of California as well as that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from which the orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do things like this because they first and above all see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They don't interfere with the "sovereign prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those with a solid emergency aid mechanism will truly have to answer for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The Chancellor's electorate in Germany, Angela Merkel, hates this kind of rescue because they know exactly who will be left with it.
The Germans oppose everything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also bears its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank that wasn't accountable but now has taken an excessively monetary policy, thus critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece and Spain).
Germany's enormous current surpluses worsen their situation to that extent.
In addition, his fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited significantly from the creation of the euro.
She should return the favor.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She needs to provide more financial support.
Isn't she the best placed to pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that would lead Europe towards more profound political integration.
We can only hope.
